The '''Awin–Pa''' or '''Awin–Pare''' languages – or, more precisely, '''Awin–Pa–Kamula''' – are a small [[language family|family]] of the [[Trans–New Guinea languages]] (TNG)

The languages are just three, [[Aekyowm language|Aekyowm]] (Awin), [[Pa language|Pare]]<!--"Pare" is better known as a Bantu language, so "Pa" is the name of the WP article--> (Pa) and [[Kamula language|Kamula]]. They are not obviously related to each other, but Aekyowm and Pare are closer to each other than to Kamula.<ref name="Suter-Usher">Edgar Suter & Timothy Usher, 2017, 'The Kamula–Elevala Language Family', ''Language & Linguistics in Melanesia'', vol. 25.</ref> 
*[[Kamula language|Kamula]]
*Awin–Pa AKA Elevala River 
**[[Aekyowm language|Aekyowm]] (Awin)
**[[Pa language|Pare]] (Pa)

The pronouns appear to have been 1sg *nɔ, 2sg *ɡo, 3sg *yɔ. Awin and Pare share 2du *gi.

Stephen Wurm (1975) added Awin and Pa to an expanded [[Central and South New Guinea languages|Central and South New Guinea]] branch of TNG, a position reversed by Ross (2005). The connection to Kamula was established by Usher.

